                We may ſooner win men by perſwaſion then by compulſion, rather by fair meanes and a ſweet language, then by foul means and rough terms: as it appeareth by that parable which Damaſcen ſetteth down, of the conteſtation betwixt the Sun and the Wind, which of them was moſt powerfull to make the traveller caſt off his cloak, who the faſter the wind blew, the faſter he held his cloak about him; but the Sun, with the influence of his firſt ſweet, and then piercing beams made him quickly to caſt off both his cloak and his coat.

